                        <seg type="rubrication">Nomina sacra; name of the donor(s); first line in
                           the incipit of Texts I and III and first word in the incipit of Text II;
                           the initial word of some sections of Text I (fols. 3r, 5r); Trinitarian
                           formula (or part of it); the words masqal (and its abbreviation) and
                           ʾaganǝnt (fol. 27r); some words written interlineally (e.g., fol. 52v);
                           elements of the punctuation signs and the text dividers; elements of
                           Ethiopic numerals.</seg>
                     </handNote>
                     <handNote xml:id="h2" script="Ethiopic">The handwriting is uniform and remains
                        rather regular throughout the
                        Ms.<!--The names of this hands need to be replaced by appropriate refs.--></handNote>
                     <handNote xml:id="h3" script="Ethiopic"> Some distinctive
                        features:<!--The names of this hands need to be replaced by appropriate refs.--></handNote>
                     <handNote xml:id="h4" script="Ethiopic"> - right-sloping
                        letters<!--The names of this hands need to be replaced by appropriate refs.--></handNote>
                     <handNote xml:id="h5" script="Ethiopic"> - ዕ, in the 6th order, is angular,
